initialValue() is called only once per thread when you call get()

So that mean you are getting only one Formatter object in both lines above

and since Formatter.format method Writes a formatted string to the Formatter object&#39;s destination (internal buffer in Formatter method)

then since you are making it equal String java will auto call toString() on the formatter.

So first time the toString will write the buffer contents which is the correct content  &quot;a and b&quot;

but second time it will write the full buffer since you didnt flush the buffer &quot;a and bc and d&quot;

the fix is easy

    final String firstValue = textFormatter.get().format(&quot;%s and %s&quot;, &quot;a&quot;,&quot;b&quot;);
    textFormatter.get().flush();
    final String secondValue = textFormatter.get().format(&quot;%s and %s&quot;, &quot;c&quot;,&quot;d&quot;);
    textFormatter.get().flush();

By default Formatter uses a StringBuilder to keep the result of format.
You can erase old formatted values by erasing the StringBuilder:

```java
StringBuilder out = (StringBuilder) textFormatter.get().out();
final String firstValue = textFormatter.get().format(&quot;%s and %s&quot;, &quot;a&quot;,&quot;b&quot;);
out.delete(0, out.length());
final String secondValue = textFormatter.get().format(&quot;%s and %s&quot;, &quot;c&quot;,&quot;d&quot;);
out.delete(0, out.length());
```

